===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|smilen||to smile|lang=enm}}, of {{etyl|gmq|en}} origin, from {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|smile||to smile|lang=da}}, from {{etyl|non|-}} {{m|non|*smíla||to smile}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*smīlijaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*smirōną||to smile}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*(s)meyh₂-||to laugh, be glad, wonder}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|smila||to smile|lang=sv}}, Low German {{term|smielen||to smile|lang=nds}}, Dutch {{term|smuilen||to smile|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|smielen||to smile|lang=gmh}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{m|goh|smierōn||to smile}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|smerian||to laugh at|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|smercian|lang=ang}}, {{term|smearcian||to smile|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|miror||to wonder at|lang=la}}. More at {{l|en|smirk}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

#A facial [[expression]] comprised by [[flex]]ing the [[muscle]]s of both ends of one's [[mouth]], often showing the front [[tooth|teeth]], without [[vocalisation]], and in humans is a common involuntary or voluntary expression of [[happiness]], [[pleasure]], [[amusement]] or [[anxiety]].
#:{{ux|en|She's got a perfect '''smile'''.&emsp; He has a sinister '''smile'''.&emsp; She had a '''smile''' on her face.&emsp; He always puts a '''smile''' on my face.}}
#*{{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=5
|passage=Then came a maid with hand-bag and shawls, and after her a tall young lady.{{...}}She looked around expectantly, and recognizing Mrs. Cooke's maid{{...}}Miss Thorn greeted her with a '''smile''' which greatly prepossessed us in her favor.}}
#*{{RQ:EHough PrqsPrc|I|0105}}
#*:Captain Edward Carlisle, soldier as he was, martinet as he was, felt a curious sensation of helplessness seize upon him as he met her steady gaze, her alluring '''smile '''; he could not tell what this prisoner might do.

